Accounts and repositories Streamlit app: not available GitHub-repo: https://github.com/marensofiesteen/IND320-streamlit/tree/main

Purpose: Briefly document the data, preprocessing, and a simple EDA (exploratory data analasis) as the fundation for the Streamlit app.

App: Interactive visualization can be found in main.py

Data: File: open-meteo-subset.csv Elhub: https://api.elhub.no/energy-data/v0/price-areas Website: https://open-meteo.com/en/docs

AI use: Throughout the project, I used ChatGPT as a support tool for troubleshooting, code review, and improving structure and readability. It helped me debug Streamlit errors, reorganize mu project into a multi-page setup, and write cleaner, more consistent Python code. I also used it to refine explanations, write short documentation, and ensure that the application met the assignment requirements. However, ChatGTP had clear limitations - it could not fully understand my specific file structure, debug live code execution, or make design decisions for me, so I had to test, adjust, and reason through several issues on my own.

Project Development Log: I initially had some issues with installing dependencies in the terminal, so I had to rund the setup through Jupyter Noebook instead. It was a bit inefficient, but it turned out to be a good learning experience and made it easier to replicate the setup for others. The project started with Elhub and Open-Meteo data. After cleaning and standardizing the datasets, I implemented STL decomposition, spectrograms, and outlier detection (SATV/SPC and LOF), and verified the analyses using Plotly visualizations. I then encountered several issues with the Streamlit app, which led me to rebuild it from scratch. I reorganizied the structure to use multiple pages instead of placing everything in main.py, which made the codebase much cleaner and easier to navigate. I also consolidated all files under the IND320-streamlit folder (they were scattered before), and created utils/io_utils.py and analysis_utils.py. The first one reads Elhub- and Open-Meteo-CSV files from data/, clean it and then stores them in st.session_state for use across pages. The second one performs and visualizes the core analyses. Finally, I added the last two pages to the app and arranged them in the correct order, completing a clean, modular structure for the entire Streamlit project. I also had some issues conecting to MongoDB, as it kept switching between MongoDB Atlad and my local MongoDB instance. The solution was to always refer to MongoDB using the full connection UTL, ensuring that I was connected to the correct instance.

# ---  Load Elhub Data (Atlas first, CSV fallback) ---

# 1) Read Mongo-innstall from secrets.toml (same as Streamlit)
cfg = tomllib.loads(pathlib.Path(".streamlit/secrets.toml").read_text())
MONGO_URI = cfg["mongo"]["uri"]
DB_NAME   = cfg["mongo"]["db"]
COL_NAME  = cfg["mongo"]["collection"]

# 2) Try Atlas first
df_elhub = None
try:
    client = MongoClient(MONGO_URI, serverSelectionTimeoutMS=5000)
    # Force a ping to valitdate the connection
    client.admin.command("ping")

    col = client[DB_NAME][COL_NAME]
    proj = {"_id": 0,
            "priceArea": 1, "productionGroup": 1, "quantityKwh": 1,
            "startTime": 1, "endTime": 1, "lastUpdatedTime": 1}

    sample = col.find_one({}, proj)
    if sample is None:
        raise RuntimeError("Atlas collection is empty")

    # Fetch all data (optionally add a filter if you want to limit it)
    docs = list(col.find({}, proj))
    df_elhub = pd.DataFrame(docs)
    print(" Loaded from MongoDB Atlas")

except Exception as e:
    print(f" Atlas unavailable or empty  loading from CSV instead ({e})")
    # 3) CSV fallback
    possible_paths = [
        Path("data/elhub_production_2021_all_areas.csv"),
        Path("elhub_production_2021_all_areas.csv"),
        Path("../elhub_production_2021_all_areas.csv"),
    ]
    csv_path = next((p for p in possible_paths if p.exists()), None)
    if csv_path is None:
        raise FileNotFoundError("Couldn't find 'elhub_production_2021_all_areas.csv'")
    df_elhub = pd.read_csv(csv_path)
    print(f" Loaded from CSV: {csv_path}")

# 4) Clean up column names and data types (robust for both sources)
#    If you want to use lowercase in the rest of the notebook:
rename_map = {
    "priceArea": "pricearea",
    "productionGroup": "productiongroup",
    "quantityKwh": "quantitykwh",
    "startTime": "starttime",
    "endTime": "endtime",
    "lastUpdatedTime": "lastupdatedtime",
}
df_elhub.rename(columns={k: v for k, v in rename_map.items() if k in df_elhub.columns}, inplace=True)

# Dates (PyMongo already provides datetime objects, but pd.to_datetime is safe in any case)
for col in ["starttime", "endtime", "lastupdatedtime"]:
    if col in df_elhub.columns:
        df_elhub[col] = pd.to_datetime(df_elhub[col], errors="coerce", utc=True)

if "quantitykwh" in df_elhub.columns:
    df_elhub["quantitykwh"] = pd.to_numeric(df_elhub["quantitykwh"], errors="coerce")

print(" Elhub data loaded and cleaned")
print(df_elhub.shape)
print(df_elhub.columns.tolist())
display(df_elhub.head(3))

# Kopied from Open-Meteo: https://open-meteo.com/en/docs/historical-reanalysis-api

def load_data_fromAPI(longitude, latitude, selected_year):
	# Setup the Open-Meteo API client with cache and retry on error
	cache_session = requests_cache.CachedSession('.cache', expire_after = -1)
	retry_session = retry(cache_session, retries = 5, backoff_factor = 0.2)
	openmeteo = openmeteo_requests.Client(session = retry_session)

	# Make sure all required weather variables are listed here
	# The order of variables in hourly or daily is important to assign them correctly below
	url = "https://archive-api.open-meteo.com/v1/archive"
	params = {
		"latitude": latitude,
		"longitude": longitude,
		"start_date": f"{selected_year}-01-01",
		"end_date": f"{selected_year}-12-31",
		"hourly": ["temperature_2m", "precipitation", "wind_speed_10m", "wind_direction_10m", "wind_gusts_10m"],
		"models": "era5",
		"timezone": "auto", # Use local timezone of the coordinates
		"wind_speed_unit": "ms", # meters per second
	}
	responses = openmeteo.weather_api(url, params=params)

	# Process first location. Add a for-loop for multiple locations or weather models
	response = responses[0]
	print(f"Coordinates: {response.Latitude()}N {response.Longitude()}E")
	print(f"Date_range: {params['start_date']} - {params['end_date']}")
	print(f"Variables: {params['hourly']}")
	# print(f"Elevation: {response.Elevation()} m asl")
	# print(f"Timezone: {response.Timezone()}{response.TimezoneAbbreviation()}")
	# print(f"Timezone difference to GMT+0: {response.UtcOffsetSeconds()}s")

	# Process hourly data. The order of variables needs to be the same as requested.
	hourly = response.Hourly()
	hourly_temperature_2m = hourly.Variables(0).ValuesAsNumpy()
	hourly_precipitation = hourly.Variables(1).ValuesAsNumpy()
	hourly_wind_speed_10m = hourly.Variables(2).ValuesAsNumpy()
	hourly_wind_direction_10m = hourly.Variables(3).ValuesAsNumpy()
	hourly_wind_gusts_10m = hourly.Variables(4).ValuesAsNumpy()

	hourly_data = {"date": pd.date_range(
		start = pd.to_datetime(hourly.Time(), unit = "s", utc = True),
		end =  pd.to_datetime(hourly.TimeEnd(), unit = "s", utc = True),
		freq = pd.Timedelta(seconds = hourly.Interval()),
		inclusive = "left"
	)}

	hourly_data["temperature_2m"] = hourly_temperature_2m
	hourly_data["precipitation"] = hourly_precipitation
	hourly_data["wind_speed_10m"] = hourly_wind_speed_10m
	hourly_data["wind_direction_10m"] = hourly_wind_direction_10m
	hourly_data["wind_gusts_10m"] = hourly_wind_gusts_10m

	hourly_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(hourly_data)
	hourly_dataframe["date"] = hourly_dataframe["date"].dt.tz_convert("Europe/Oslo")
	return hourly_dataframe

  1. SATV with DCT + SPC-bounderies

def satv_spc_plot(df, dct_cutoff=365, n_sigma=3.0,
                  time_col="date", temp_col="temperature_2m"):
    """
    High-pass DCT (SATV) + SPC outliers p temperatur.

    Parametre
    ---------
    dct_cutoff : int
        Antall lavfrekvente koeffisienter som beholdes i trend (hyere = glattere trend).
        SATV = original - trend.
    n_sigma : float
        Antall robust-standardavvik (MAD*1.4826) for SPC-grenser.
    """

    data = df[[time_col, temp_col]].dropna().copy()
    data = data.sort_values(time_col)
    y = data[temp_col].to_numpy(dtype=float)

    # DCT (type II), build the trend by seroing out high-frequency components.
    Y = dct(y, type=2, norm="ortho")
    Y_hp = Y.copy()
    Y_hp[:dct_cutoff] = 0.0    # Keep low-frequency components in the trend => zero them out in the high-pass
    satv = idct(Y_hp, type=2, norm="ortho")

    # Robust SPC boundaries on the SATV
    med = np.median(satv)
    mad = np.median(np.abs(satv - med))
    robust_std = 1.4826 * mad if mad > 0 else satv.std(ddof=1)
    upper = med + n_sigma * robust_std
    lower = med - n_sigma * robust_std

    is_out = (satv > upper) | (satv < lower)

    out_summary = (pd.DataFrame({
        time_col: data[time_col].values,
        "SATV": satv,
        "is_outlier": is_out
    })
    .loc[is_out]
    .assign(direction=lambda x: np.where(x["SATV"]>0, "high", "low"))
    )

    # Plot
    fig = go.Figure()

    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
        x=data[time_col], y=data[temp_col],
        mode="lines", name="Temperature (C)",
        hovertemplate="%{x|%Y-%m-%d %H:%M}<br>%{y:.2f} C"
    ))

    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
        x=data[time_col], y=satv,
        mode="lines", name="SATV (C)", opacity=0.6
    ))

    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
        x=data[time_col], y=np.full(len(data), upper),
        mode="lines", name="SPC upper", line=dict(dash="dash")
    ))
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
        x=data[time_col], y=np.full(len(data), lower),
        mode="lines", name="SPC lower", line=dict(dash="dash")
    ))

    if is_out.any():
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
            x=data.loc[is_out, time_col], y=satv[is_out],
            mode="markers", name="Outliers (SATV)",
            marker=dict(size=7, symbol="x")
        ))

    fig.update_layout(
        title=f"Temperature with SATV & SPC (cutoff={dct_cutoff}, n_sigma={n_sigma})",
        xaxis_title="Time", yaxis_title="C", legend_title="Legend"
    )

    return fig, out_summary

In[]:
def precipitation_lof_plot(df, contamination=0.01,
                          time_col="date", precip_col="precipitation",
                          n_neighbors=20):
    """
    LOF-anomalies on precipitation.
    Contamination : proportion of expected outliers (default 1%)
    """

    data = df[[time_col, precip_col]].dropna().copy()
    data = data.sort_values(time_col)
    X = data[[precip_col]].to_numpy()

    # LOF
    lof = LocalOutlierFactor(n_neighbors=n_neighbors, contamination=contamination)
    labels = lof.fit_predict(X)   # -1 = outlier
    scores = -lof.negative_outlier_factor_  # higher = more deviations

    data["lof_score"] = scores
    data["is_outlier"] = labels == -1

    # Plot
    fig = px.scatter(
        data, x=time_col, y=precip_col, color="is_outlier",
        title=f"Precipitation & LOF anomalies (contamination={contamination}, n_neighbors={n_neighbors})",
        labels={precip_col: "Precipitation (mm)", time_col: "Time"}
    )

    summary = data.loc[data["is_outlier"], [time_col, precip_col, "lof_score"]].copy()
    summary = summary.sort_values("lof_score", ascending=False)

    return fig, summary

def _prepare_series(
    df: pd.DataFrame,
    price_area: str,
    production_group: str,
    start: Optional[pd.Timestamp] = None,
    end: Optional[pd.Timestamp] = None,
    time_col: str = "starttime",
    value_col: str = "quantitykwh",
    freq: str = "H",
) -> pd.Series:
    """
    Filter Elhub data to a single (price_area, production_group), select time range,
    sort, set a uniform hourly frequency, and lightly fill gaps.

    Returns a pandas Series indexed by a uniform DateTimeIndex (freq='H').
    """

    # Defensive typing/conversion
    dfx = df.copy()
    if not np.issubdtype(dfx[time_col].dtype, np.datetime64):
        dfx[time_col] = pd.to_datetime(dfx[time_col], errors="coerce")

    # Filter
    m = dfx["pricearea"].eq(price_area)
    m &= dfx["productiongroup"].eq(production_group)
    dfx = dfx.loc[m, [time_col, value_col]].dropna()

    # Time range
    if start is not None:
        dfx = dfx[dfx[time_col] >= pd.to_datetime(start)]
    if end is not None:
        dfx = dfx[dfx[time_col] <= pd.to_datetime(end)]

    # Index + sort
    dfx = dfx.sort_values(time_col).set_index(time_col)

    # Ensure regular hourly frequency (fill tiny gaps safely)
    s = dfx[value_col].asfreq(freq)
    # Fill short gaps (forward-fill 1 step, then small interpolation)
    s = s.ffill(limit=1).interpolate(limit=6)

    # If completely empty, raise a helpful error
    if s.dropna().empty:
        raise ValueError(
            f"No data after filtering for price_area={price_area}, group={production_group}, "
            f"range=({start}  {end})."
        )

    return s
  1. STL decomposition function STK splits the signal into seasonal, trend and remainder. With hourly data, a natural seasonal period is 168 hours (one week). The seasonal_smoother and trend_smoother control the LOESS window lengths (larger->smoother curves). robust=True downweights outliers during the fit. The function returns both the figure and the fitted object so you can access arrays via stl.seasonal, stl.trend, and stl.resid
In[32]:
def _ensure_odd(n: int, minimum: int = 3) -> int:
    """Ensure that n is an odd integer >= minimum."""
    n = int(n)
    if n < minimum:
        n = minimum
    if n % 2 == 0:
        n += 1 # make odd
    return n

def stl_decompose_production(
    df: pd.DataFrame,
    price_area: str,
    production_group: str,
    period_length: int = 168,        # 168 = weekly seasonality with hourly data
    seasonal_smoother: int = 7,      # LOESS smoother for seasonal component
    trend_smoother: int = 31*24,     # ~monthly trend smoother (in hours)
    robust: bool = True,
    start: pd.Timestamp | None = None,
    end: pd.Timestamp | None = None,
    freq: str = "h",
) -> Tuple[go.Figure, STL]:
    """
    Run STL (Seasonal-Trend decomposition using LOESS) on hourly production data.

    Excepts columns: ["pricearea", "productiongroup", "datetime", "quantitykwh"]
    Returns (fig, stl_result)
    """
    # 1) Filter + guard rails
    needed = {"pricearea", "productiongroup", "datetime", "quantitykwh"}
    missing = needed - set(df.columns)
    if missing:
        raise ValueError(f"DataFrame is missing required columns: {sorted(missing)}")
    
    d = (
        df[(df["pricearea"] == price_area) & (df["productiongroup"] == production_group)]
        .dropna(subset=["datetime", "quantitykwh"])
        .copy()
    )
    if start is not None:
        d = d[d["datetime"] >= pd.to_datetime(start)]
    if end is not None:
        d = d[d["datetime"] <= pd.to_datetime(end)]
    
    if d.empty:
        raise ValueError(
            f"No rows found for price_area={price_area!r}, production_group={production_group!r}, "
            f"with the given date range."
        )

    # 2) Index on datetime and enforce hourly frequency
    d["datetime"] = pd.to_datetime(d["datetime"], errors="coerce", utc=True)
    d = d.sort_values("datetime").set_index("datetime")
    # This will create hourly grid and insert NaNs where any hours are missing:
    d = d.asfreq(freq)

    # 3) Numerival series and simple gap filling
    y = pd.to_numeric(d["quantitykwh"], errors="coerce").ffill()
    # First try linear interpolation, then forward/backward fill as safety
    y = y.interpolate(limit_direction="both").ffill().bfill()

    #4) Validate STL parameters:
    seasonal_smoother = _ensure_odd(seasonal_smoother, minimum=7)
    trend_smoother = _ensure_odd(trend_smoother, minimum=3)

    if trend_smoother <= seasonal_smoother:
        # ensure STL constraint: trend > period"
        trend_smoother = _ensure_odd(period_length + 1)
    
    # Also ensure we have enough samples:
    if len(y) < (period_length + trend_smoother + seasonal_smoother):
        raise ValueError(
            "Not enough data points for the chosen STL windows. "
            f"len(y)={len(y)}, period={period_length}, seasonal_smoother={seasonal_smoother}, trend={trend_smoother}."
            f"seasonal={seasonal_smoother}, trend={trend_smoother}."
        )

    # 5) Run STL
    stl = STL(
        y,
        period=int(period_length),
        seasonal=int(seasonal_smoother),
        trend=int(trend_smoother),
        robust=robust,
    ).fit()

    # 6) Build Plotly figure (4 rows)
    t = y.index

    fig = make_subplots(
        rows=4, cols=1, shared_xaxes=True, vertical_spacing=0.03,
        subplot_titles=("Original", "Trend", "Seasonal", "Remainder")
    )

    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=t, y=y,  name="Original", mode="lines"), row=1, col=1)
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=t, y=stl.trend, name="Trend",    mode="lines"), row=2, col=1)
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=t, y=stl.seasonal, name="Seasonal", mode="lines"), row=3, col=1)
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=t, y=stl.resid, name="Remainder", mode="lines"), row=4, col=1)

    fig.update_layout(
        height=900,
        title=f"STL Decomposition  {price_area} / {production_group} "
              f"(period={period_length}, seasonal={seasonal_smoother}, trend={trend_smoother}, robust={robust})",
        xaxis4_title="Time",
        yaxis_title="kWh",
        template="plotly_white",
        legend=dict(orientation="h", y=1.03, x=0.5, xanchor="center"),
        margin=dict(t=90)
    )

    return fig, stl
In[33]:
def normalize_elhub_columns(df_in: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    lower_map = {c.lower(): c for c in df_in.columns}
    def pick(*names):
        for n in names:
            if n in lower_map:
                return lower_map[n]
        return None

    col_time = pick("datetime", "starttime", "time", "start_time")
    col_qty = pick("quantitykwh", "quantity", "kwh", "value")
    col_area = pick("pricearea", "price_area")
    col_grp = pick("productiongroup", "production_group")

    if None in (col_time, col_qty, col_area, col_grp):
        raise KeyError("Required columns missing in df_elhub")

    df = df_in.rename(columns={
        col_time: "datetime",
        col_qty: "quantitykwh",
        col_area: "pricearea",
        col_grp: "productiongroup"
    })

    df["datetime"] = pd.to_datetime(df["datetime"], errors="coerce", utc=True)
    df["quantitykwh"] = pd.to_numeric(df["quantitykwh"], errors="coerce")
    try:
        df["datetime"] = df["datetime"].dt.tz_convert("Europe/Oslo")
    except:
        pass

    return df

df_elhub_norm = normalize_elhub_columns(df_elhub)

  1. Spectrogram of Electricity Production Data: In this step, we analyze the frequency content of the electricity production data using a spectrogram. While a normal time-series plot shows hos production changes over time, a spectrogram shows which patterns repeat, how often they repeat, and when they occur.

# --- Imports (once per notebook) ---
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import plotly.graph_objects as go
from scipy.signal import stft

def spectrogram_production(
    df: pd.DataFrame,
    price_area: str,
    production_group: str,
    window_length_hours: int = 168,   # 1 week
    window_overlap: float = 0.5,      # 50% overlap
    detrend: str = "constant",        # or "linear"
    scaling: str = "density",         # "spectrum" also works
    clip_db: tuple[float, float] | None = (-80, 20),  # color scale clamp in dB
):
    """
    Compute a time-frequency spectrogram of hourly production (quantitykwh).
    Returns a Plotly Figure and the (f, t_mid, Sxx_db) arrays for further analysis.

    Parameters
    ----------
    df : DataFrame with columns ['pricearea','productiongroup','datetime','quantitykwh']
    price_area, production_group : filters
    window_length_hours : STFT window length in samples (hours)
    window_overlap : fraction in [0,1). e.g. 0.5 = 50% overlap
    detrend : passed to scipy.signal.stft
    scaling : passed to scipy.signal.stft
    clip_db : (vmin, vmax) for color scale in dB. Use None for auto.

    Notes
    -----
    - Sampling rate is 1 sample per hour (fs = 1.0). Frequencies (cycles per hour)
      are converted to period in *days* for labeling, i.e. period_days = 24 / f_cph.
    """
    # 1) Filter and hourly series
    d = (
        df[(df["pricearea"] == price_area) & (df["productiongroup"] == production_group)]
        .dropna(subset=["datetime", "quantitykwh"])
        .sort_values("datetime")
        .copy()
    )
    if d.empty:
        raise ValueError(f"No data for {price_area=}, {production_group=}")

    d = d.set_index("datetime").asfreq("h")
    y = pd.to_numeric(d["quantitykwh"], errors="coerce").ffill().values  # 1 sample/hour
    t_index = d.index

    # 2) STFT
    fs = 1.0  # samples per hour
    nperseg = int(window_length_hours)
    noverlap = int(window_overlap * nperseg)
    if nperseg < 8:
        raise ValueError("window_length_hours too small; use at least 8")

    f, t_bins, Zxx = stft(
        y,
        fs=fs,
        window="hann",
        nperseg=nperseg,
        noverlap=noverlap,
        detrend=detrend,
        return_onesided=True,
        boundary=None,
        padded=False,
        scaling=scaling,
    )
    # Power (magnitude^2) -> dB
    Sxx = np.abs(Zxx) ** 2
    Sxx_db = 10 * np.log10(Sxx + 1e-12)

    # 3) Map STFT time bins (center of each window) to real datetimes
    # t_bins is in hours since start; convert to timestamps:
    t0 = t_index[0]
    t_mid = pd.to_datetime(t0) + pd.to_timedelta(t_bins, unit="h")

    # 4) Convert frequency (cycles/hour) to period in days for the y-axis
    f_cph = f.copy()
    with np.errstate(divide="ignore"):
        period_days = 24.0 / f_cph
    # Mask very long periods (DC or near-zero freq) for display
    valid = np.isfinite(period_days) & (period_days <= 120)  # hide > ~4 months
    period_days = period_days[valid]
    Sxx_db = Sxx_db[valid, :]

    # 5) Optional clipping for a cleaner color scale
    if clip_db is not None:
        vmin, vmax = clip_db
        Sxx_db = np.clip(Sxx_db, vmin, vmax)

    # 6) Build Plotly heatmap (x=time, y=period_days, color=power dB)
    fig = go.Figure(
        data=go.Heatmap(
            x=t_mid,
            y=period_days,
            z=Sxx_db,
            colorscale="Viridis",
            colorbar=dict(title="Power (dB)"),
            zsmooth=False,
        )
    )
    fig.update_layout(
        title=f"Spectrogram  {price_area} / {production_group} "
              f"(window={window_length_hours}h, overlap={int(window_overlap*100)}%)",
        xaxis_title="Time",
        yaxis_title="Period (days)",
        template="plotly_white",
        height=600,
    )
    # Invert y-axis so shorter periods (high frequency) are at the top (optional):
    fig.update_yaxes(autorange="reversed")

    return fig, (f, t_mid, Sxx_db)

# --- Example usage (pick a real combination that exists in your data) ---
fig_spec, arrays = spectrogram_production(
    df_elhub_norm,
    price_area="NO1",
    production_group="other",
    window_length_hours=168,   # 1 week window
    window_overlap=0.5,        # 50% overlap
    detrend="constant",
    scaling="psd",
    clip_db=(-60, 20)
)
fig_spec.show()
